#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:15
msgid ""
"This is meant to provide a technical specification for the minimal syntax"
" of ``backup.json``, as read and written by "
":mod:`psp.processors.json_processor`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:21
msgid "Terminology"
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:23
msgid "Here are some terms that will be used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:32
msgid "attribute"
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:26
msgid ""
"An attribute is a pair of name and value, similar to key and value of a "
"Python *dict*.  For example the ``tz`` attribute (or more verbosely, the "
"value of the attribute with the name ``tz``) is a string and the ``data``"
" attribute of entries may be a *str* or *bool*.  To make it consistent I "
"will use code literals for attribute names (like ``tz`` and ``data``) and"
" italic for variables types (like *dict* and *str*) and names (like "
"*panels* and *entries*)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:35
msgid "field"
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:35
msgid "Another name for attribute.  Sometimes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:40
msgid "*dict*, *list*, *str*, *bool*, null"
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:38
msgid ""
"These will be convenient Pythonic terms to refer to JSON objects, arrays,"
" strings, and booleans.  (They are used mainly because object means "
"something different in Python; the use of null is preserved however.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:44
msgid "*text*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:43
msgid ""
"When an attribute is a *text* attribute, it must be either a *str* or a "
"*list* of *str* (such that ``''.join()`` can create a string from it)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:46
msgid ""
"Other terms such as \"panel\" and \"entry\" will be explained "
"progressively in the following text."
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:52
msgid "Top-Level Attributes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:54
msgid ""
"A backup file is always a *dict*, inside which are what we will call the "
"*top-level attributes* and a *list* of *panels* stored under the key "
"``data``.  Here we will enumerate several keys (all surprisingly "
"optional) that you may use."
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:63
msgid "tz (optional)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:60
msgid ""
"A *str* representing the time zone for everything in this backup. Must be"
" valid when passed to :meth:`JSONLoader.parse_timezone`. This is optional"
" but a time zone must be eventually provided as :class:`JSONLoader` "
"parses some time/date time string."
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:73
msgid "paths (optional)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:66
msgid ""
"A *list* of *str* for the lookup paths.  Each time the ``input`` "
"attribute of an *entry* is parsed, its value is prepended with the "
"``base_dir`` option of :class:`JSONLoader` and a path in this attribute."
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:70
msgid ""
"By default this evaluates to simply ``['.']``---that is, the same "
"directory as ``base_dir``.  If this is not omitted, however, be noted "
"that ``\".\"`` will not be automatically added and you have to explicitly"
" add it if you want :class:`JSONLoader` to look in the same directory as "
"``base_dir``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:78
msgid "data (optional)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:76
msgid ""
"A *list* of *dict*, each *dict* being what is called a *panel*.  The "
"content of each *dict* is elaborated in the following section. An empty "
"list is assumed if this is omitted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:80
msgid ""
"Any other key is ignored by :class:`JSONLoader`, though there is one key "
"that is recommended for you to use.  It is also addressed because "
":class:`JSONDumper` exports it and the ``psp synopsis`` command "
"recognizes it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:87
msgid "desc"
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:86
msgid "A *text* attribute giving a brief description of this backup file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:91
msgid "Panels"
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:93
msgid ""
"Now for the panels!  A *panel* is a container of *entries*, loosely "
"speaking. It does cooler stuff than that though, but first let's talk "
"about the one and only **required** attribute:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:99
msgid "date"
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:98
msgid ""
"A *str* representing the date of the panel.  Must be valid when passed to"
" :meth:`JSONLoader.parse_date`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:101
msgid "For providing entries:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:106
msgid "entries (optional)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:104
msgid ""
"A *list* of *dict*, each *dict* being what is called an *entry*. The "
"content of each *dict* is elaborated in the following section. An empty "
"list is assumed if this is omitted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:108
msgid "There is only one valid optional attribute:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:116
msgid "rating (optional)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:111
msgid ""
"A *str* representing the rating of the panel (can be null).  The three "
"ratings from Perspective from bad to good are represented with the "
"strings ``\":(\"``, ``\":|\"``, and ``\":)\"``. (I did not use numbers "
"because I'm not a nerd >_>)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:116
msgid "Rating is set to null when omitted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:149
msgid "Entries"
msgstr ""

#: ../../struct/backup-spec.rst:151
msgid ""
"Now for the entries... this can get tricky since this is where most of "
"the things take place."
msgstr ""

